WOrdw_L2CAcn9rw==)nium was chosen because it maintains its structural integrity at high temperatures, whereas aluminum would have softened and failed.\n*   [2](https://simpleflying.com/aircraft-lockheed-built-so-fast-pilots-dont-fully-understand-worked/), [9](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHTzcN-5GPTTKTFma2F4530IzoBP3QJMNjAlAV80wAgqSZS79c_k3p0fRl1jGLVyY0TZ-QXW5KDBeHjP3LYO-90E4jRYkx29Qobn5H3kzPE1r25Df6GMGro4XEgfWqnvhpWOrdw_L2CAcn9rw==)**Unique Sourcing:** Interestingly, during the Cold War, the U.S. procured much of this titanium from the Soviet Union, the world\u2019s largest supplier, by using third-party countries and front companies to avoid detection.\n*   **[10](https://www.reddit.com/r/AskEngineers/comments/g9xkpq/was_any_type_of_carbon_fibre_ever_considered_for/), [11](https://www.quora.com/What-material-would-you-use-if-you-were-to-build-an-aircraft-like-the-SR-71-Blackbird-today)Composite Materials:** About 15% of the aircraft consisted of high-temperature polymer composite materials.\n*   **[8](https://tmstitanium.com/news-post/the-lockheed-sr-71-blackbird)Specialized Coatings:** The aircraft was finished with a specialized \"radar-absorbent\" black paint with high emissivity. This d[7](https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/sr71-blackbird/252077846)ark color helped radiate heat away from the aircraft, and the emissivity was critical for thermal management.\n*   **[7](https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/sr71-blackbird/252077846)Engine Components:** Nickel-based superalloys were utilized in the Pratt & Whitney J58 engines to withstand the extreme heat generated during high-speed operations.\n*   **[7](https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/sr71-blackbird/252077846)Quartz Glass:** The windshields were made of specialized heat-resistant quartz glass to survive the temperatures encountered at cruise speeds.\n\nBecau[7](https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/sr71-blackbird/252077846)se titanium is difficult to work with, Lockheed engineers had to develop entirely new manufacturing processes, including special tools and handling techniques (such as using distilled water for cleaning to prevent chemical contamination that could weaken the metal).[7](https://www.slideshare.net/slideshow/sr71-blackbird/252077846)"
